english:
  title: An Elegy for Master Yun, National University Administrator
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There was an extraordinary and magnanimous sage, Master Yun of Tianshui, whose name was Wei. Descended from the ancient Marshal and Court Attendant Yi Yanyi, his lineage gleamed through generations of renown. At first he dwelt hidden in the mountains, calling himself the Hermit of the Green Pine. Yet brightness such as the moon and luminous pearl cannot forever remain concealed in shadow. Thus, though reluctant, he emerged into service, ascending through honored posts until he reached the position of National University Administrator. In character he was benevolent and cultivated, upright and austere, his virtue and learning complete and flawless. He could drink several measures of wine without loss of composure. He himself declared: "Since my marriage, I have never strayed to another woman"—a feat difficult for most. In all matters, he overlooked trifles and held fast to the essential. The world perceived in him the bearing of a minister, certain he would rise far. Alas, he was appointed Western Provincial Administrator, yet never returned, but passed into the realm beyond. Oh, how Heaven's blessings fall thus! Though certain parties had stirred whispers against him—whispers even he scarcely comprehended—fate's thread was cut. When I served as records keeper in Jeonju, I fell into disfavor with colleagues. The Master, now an Inspector, showed me such warmth from our former friendship that he treated me abundantly, while dealing harshly with others. This bred resentment, and later through dark insinuation, damage was done. Such truth cannot remain hidden forever. When the Master departed from life, I grieved as one loses an elder brother. I composed this dirge:

    Generation after generation your line descends unbroken,
    Brilliance shining bright through the ages.
    Some seized the golden axe of command,
    Crushing the barbarian tribes in triumph.
    Blessings flowed like waters long,
    Spilling forth to your descendants.
    Stately stood our Master,
    Inborn spirit towering high.

    At first he withdrew, as the dragon coils in sleep,
    Then suddenly he emerged, as the phoenix spreads its wings.
    To gaze upon him inspired awe—unapproachable, commanding reverence.
    To draw near him brought warmth—radiant as the sun.

    He trod the straight path without becoming narrow,
    His breadth expansive yet never scattered.
    Drinking deeply, his spirit remained composed,
    His lofty thoughts flowed in mighty strokes.
    His prose was elegant and forceful,
    His verses spirited and wild.

    All said the Master was fit for highest office,
    The realm thirsted for his guidance like parched earth for rain.
    Yet the post of Administrator seemed not lowly—
    Was this not but a stepping stone? Time remained.
    But who loosed such wicked tongues,
    Disturbing the very wheels of fate?
    They sent the Master westward,
    To bow beneath the provincial chair.
    Heaven darkened his prospects—
    This was the omen.
    With broken wing he departed,
    Never to return.

    The jade groves, the pearl trees—their radiance dimmed!
    Yet his words remain,
    Worth singing to the strings of gold.
    Once Yang Cheng went forth as magistrate in this same post,
    And his students rushed to the palace,
    Thronging the courts with petition.
    Though the sovereign did not heed,
    Their righteousness endured.
    They stirred the shallow age,
    Polishing the frivolous spirit.

    But with the Master gone, where are his followers now?
    Alas for this diminished world—
    Who would beg him to stay?
    Lonely fury kindled, consuming his very life.
    In those dim realms below,
    With whom shall he wander?

    Oh, the Master's cruel fate!
    Beginning as a man of great promise,
    Yet ending in stumbling steps.
    As for me—without the Master, who knows my heart?
    Now that he is gone, I lay down my tools,
    And sigh.

    I cry out with thunderous voice, tears falling,
    But the Master hears me not.
    What can be done?

    Still his clear wind and cool breath seem to touch us,
    Yet for all I would say in his honor,
    Words fail me.
  footnotes:
    - Yang Cheng (陽城) was a Tang Dynasty official known for his integrity and the devotion of his students; his students once petitioned the emperor when he was transferred away. Lee Gyeong-bo invokes this historical parallel to honor Master Yun.
    - The 'golden axe' (黃鉞) was a symbol of imperial authority granted to generals, representing the power of life and death in military command.
    - Master Yun's appointment as Western Provincial Administrator (西都留守) of Pyongyang effectively ended his career at court, as he died without returning to the capital.
